                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2943.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-27T18:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 27, 1912—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Emilio Vásquez Gómez, who is now in San Antonio, is apparently the leader of the
                    revolutionary movement directed against this Government. It is evident that in
                    our interests as well as in the interest of the Mexican Government he should
                    either be expelled from American territory or, under a liberal interpretation of
                    the present neutrality laws, subjected to imprisonment. Either course would have
                    a beneficial effect.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
